Y by P162008First, the recursive sequence $a_{n}$ has the characteristic equation:



$r^2 - r - x = 0 \Rightarrow r = \frac{1 \pm \sqrt{1+4x}}{2}$ (call the '+' root $K$ and the '-' root $k$ for simplicity);



and the general form $a_{n} = AK^n + Bk^n$ (for real constants $A$ & $B$).  Knowing that $a_{0}=0, a_{1}=1$, we find that $B = -A$ and $A = 1/\sqrt{1+4x}$.  Hence, $a_{n} = (1/\sqrt{1+4x}) \cdot (K^n - k^n)$.



Next, the infinite geometric series computes to:



$1 = (1/\sqrt{1+4x}) \cdot [1/(1-(K/10)) - 1/(1-(k/10))]$;



or $1 = (1/\sqrt(1+4x)) \cdot [20/(19-\sqrt{1+4x}) - 20/(19+\sqrt{1+4x})]$;



or $1 = (1/\sqrt{1+4x}) \cdot [40\sqrt{1+4x} / (361 - (1+4x))]$;



or $1 = 40/(360 - 4x)$;



or $360 - 4x = 40$;



or $4x = 320$;



or $\fbox{x = 80}$.

